-<h1>
-<a name="activeandroid" class="anchor" href="#activeandroid"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>ActiveAndroid</h1>
+<h2>
+<a id="usage" class="anchor" href="#usage" aria-hidden="true"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>Usage</h2>
 
-<p>ActiveAndroid is an active record style ORM (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Object-relational_mapping">object relational mapper</a>). What does that mean exactly? Well, ActiveAndroid allows you to save and retrieve SQLite database records without ever writing a single SQL statement. Each database record is wrapped neatly into a class with methods like <em>save()</em> and <em>delete()</em>.</p>
+<pre><code>new RxSelect&lt;MyEntity&gt;.from(MyEntity.class).where(...).execute().subscribe(myEntitiesList -&gt; ...);
+</code></pre>
 
 <p>ActiveAndroid does so much more than this though. Accessing the database is a hassle, to say the least, in Android. ActiveAndroid takes care of all the setup and messy stuff, and all with just a few simple steps of configuration.</p>
 
